summary: 04/11/1999: Unknown perpetrators damaged the Judaic Religious Association of Belarus and a synagogue in Minsk when they set fire to the front door and spray-painted anti-Jewish messages on the walls.
target1: The offices of the Judaic Religious Association of Belarus in Minsk
target2: Minsk synagogue sharing the building with the Judaic Religious Association
motive: Anti-Semitism was cited as the motive the attack.
propcomment: The front door and paint on the first floor of the building were damaged.
scite1: “Arsonists Attack Synagogue in Minsk,” Belapan, April 12, 1999.
scite2: Svetlana Karpekova, “Arson Attack on Minsk Judaic Association's Premises,” Izvestia, April 14, 1999.

summary: 05/30/2001: In Minsk, Belarus, two unknown individuals threw a grenade at the Russian Embassy. This attack occurred right before a summit for the Commonwealth of Independent States was to commence. The explosion damaged the wall of the Embassy.
scite1: "Grenade thrown at Russian embassy on eve of CIS summit," Deutsche Presse-Agentur, May 31, 2001.

summary: 04/03/2006: Human rights activist Mikalay Kalinin, a leader of the Gypsy community in Belarus, was attacked by six unidentified men at the intersection of Kamunistychnaya and Maksim Bahdanovich streets in Minsk, Belarus. The assailants claimed Kalinin had insulted a woman they knew. No group claimed responsibility for the attack.
addnotes: The attackers explained that they were defending the honor of a woman who was allegedly insulted by Kalinin, but Kalinin says he and his father and friend only saw the girl when he was attacked. Kalinin contended that the assault was connected with his human rights work, in particular his involvement in monitoring the presidential election, as he submitted his findings to representatives of the mission of the OSCE ODIHR (Office for Democratic Institutions and Human Rights). --Kalinin complained that he was having difficulty breathing, a sign indicating that he may have had a rib broken.
scite1: “Human rights activist attacked in Belarusian capital,” Minsk Belapan in English, April 06, 2006.

location: The bombing attack took place at the Hero City memorial, a World War II monument, in central Minsk, Minsk state, Belarus.
summary: 07/04/2008: On Friday night at 00:30, 50 people were injured when a home-made bomb exploded at the Hero City memorial, a World War II monument, in central Minsk, Minsk state, Belarus, where thousands of people had gathered for the Independence Day concert. Two Belarusian opposition activists were detained by police following the blast. No claim of responsibility was made for the incident.
target1: Civilians attending the Independence Day concert
motive: The specific motive for the attack is unknown..
weapdetail: A home-made bomb containing unknown explosives was used in the bombing attack.
propcomment: It is unknown if damage was caused by the incident.
scite1: Press TV, "Dozens Wounded in Belarus Bast," July 5, 2008, http://www.presstv.ir/Detail.aspx?id=62595&sectionid=351020606.
scite2: Belapan, "Two Belarusian Opposition Activists Detained Over Independence Day Blast," Belapan, July 9, 2008.

location: The attack took place at the Russian embassy in Minsk.
summary: 08/31/2010: On Tuesday, in Minsk, Belarus, an unidentified assailant threw two fire bombs at the Russian embassy, destroying one car while causing no casualties. Friends of Freedom claimed responsibility for the attack and six suspects have been arrested in connection with the attack.
target1: The Russian embassy was targeted in the attack.
motive: The specific motive for the attack was to show protest against the destruction of the Khimki forest for the building of a highway.
weapdetail: An unknown incendiary device was used in the attack.
propcomment: One car was destroyed in the attack.
scite1: Amie Ferris-Rotman, "Fire Bombs Thrown at Russian Embassy in Minsk," Reuters, August 31, 2010, http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/LDE67U07F.htm.
scite2: Jane’s Intelligence, “Security Forces Detain Suspected Militants in Belarus's Minsk,” Terrorism Watch Report, ITAR-TASS, September 7, 2010.
scite3: Xinhua News Agency, "Russian Group Claims Responsiblity for Attack on Russian Embassy in Belarus," Xinhua News Agency, September 2, 2010, http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2010-09/02/c_13475575.htm.

location: The attack occurred at a prison on Okrestin Street in Minsk city, Minsk, Belarus.
summary: 09/07/2010: On Tuesday, in Minsk city, Minsk, Belarus, unidentified assailants threw two Molotov cocktails at Minsk Prison on Okrestin Street, damaging the prison but causing no casualties. The Friends of Freedom claimed responsibility.
target1: A prison was targeted in the attack.
motive: The specific motive for the attack is unknown.
weapdetail: Two molotov cocktails were used in the attack.
propcomment: The attack caused minor damage to Minsk Prison.
scite1: Russia & CIS Military Newswire, "Molotov Cocktails Thrown into Minsk Jail with Detained Anarchists," LexisNexis Academic, Russia & CIS Military Newswire, September 7, 2010.
scite2: National Counterterrorism Center, "One Prison Damaged in Incendiary Attack by Friends of Freedom in Minsk, Belarus," Worldwide Incidents Tracking System, January 28, 2011.
scite3: Russia & CIS Military Newswire, "Embassy Incident in Minsk was Act of 'Disorderly Conduct' - Russian Ambassador," LexisNexis Academic, Russia & CIS Military Newswire, September 7, 2010.

location: The attack occurred at the underground Oktyabrsakaya metro station in Minsk, Belarus.
summary: 04/11/2011: On Monday afternoon at 1500, 13 people were killed and 161 were wounded when a radio-controlled bomb exploded at a metro station in Minsk, Belarus. The bomb was the equivalent of between five and seven kilograms of TNT and was filled with shrapnel and metal balls that measured about one centimeter in diameter. It was hidden underneath a bench on the platform of the Oktyabrsakaya metro station. The bombing left a crater in the platform with a diameter of 80 centimeters. No group claimed responsibility for the explosion. Viktor Dvorakovskiy, a 23-year-old man on the Russian most wanted terrorist list, is suspected of being involved in the bombing. Interpol announce on 05/13/2011, that the finger prints found at the scene of the 2011 subway bombing match those of the suspect from the 2008 Minsk bombing as well.
target1: An underground metro station was targeted in the attack.
target2: Civilians were targeted in the attack.
motive: The specific motive for the attack is unknown.
weapdetail: A bomb the equivalent of between five and seven kilograms of TNT and filled with shrapnel and metal balls was used in the attack.
propcomment: The bombing left a crater in the platform with a diameter of 80 centimeters.
scite1: Interfax, "Belarusian KGB Insists Minsk Subway Bomb Was Radio-Controlled (Part Two)," World News Connection, Interfax, April 12, 2011.
scite2: Xinhua News Agency, "Death Toll from Metro Bombing in Minsk Rises to 13," Xinhua News Agency, April 16, 2011, http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2011-04/16/c_13831272.htm.
scite3: Ekho Moskvy Radio, "Alleged Russian Wahhabi Suspected of Terrorist Attack in Minsk," World News Connection, Ekho Moskvy Radio, April 18, 2011.

summary: 05/24/2012: An assailant threw a petrol bomb at the building of the interregional department for combating organized crime in the city of Zhlobin, Gomel region, Belarus. According to officials, the petrol bomb was meant to distract police officers so the assailant could detonate a larger explosive device; however, authorities seized the attacker before he could successfully trigger the device. There were no reported casualties. No group claimed responsibility for the incident; however, security officials indicated that the assailant had connections to a criminal organization that sent Afghan nationals to European nations.
target1: Interregional Department for Combating Organized Crime
weapdetail: Five kilograms of TNT and a Molotov cocktail were used in the attack.
scite1: "Explosives, shrapnel seized from alleged Belarus would-be bomber - sources," Interfax: Russia & CIS Military Newswire, May 25, 2012.
scite2: "Explosives Confiscated During Failed Attack On Local Belarusian Police Office," Interfax, May 25, 2012.
scite3: "Terror plot with "Arab trail" foiled in Belarus," Interfax: Ukrainian General Newswire, May 25, 2012.

summary: 11/05/2012: An explosive device detonated at the Belarusian-Polish border in the Hrondna area, Grodno region, Belarus. Border guards were following the tracks of suspected illegal immigrants when they came across the blast site. The site of detonation was scattered with clothing fragments and burnt currency bills; it is unclear if anyone was injured. No group claimed responsibility for the incident.
addnotes: There is doubt that this incident meets terrorism-related criteria. It is unclear whether the blast was related to the tracking of the illegal immigrants.
scite1: "Newly Independent States," Russia & CIS Military Weekly, November 9, 2012.

summary: 11/11/2012: An explosive device detonated outside of the Committee for State Security (KGB) building in Vitsyebsk city, Vitsyebsk oblast, Belarus. There were no reported injuries; however, the building suffered some minor damages. No group claimed responsibility for the incident; however, three individuals were arrested in connection to the incident.
motive: Specific motive is unknown; however, police officials believe the attack was designed to "destabilize the situation" in the country.
weapdetail: A homemade bomb formed in a cardboard or plastic tube filled with between 50 and 70 grams of a pyrotechnic substance and non-lethal elements that was contained in a glass container between 0.25 and 0.33 liters large was used in the attack.
propcomment: Two windows were damaged in this attack.
addnotes: One of the suspects in custody suffered from a mental disorder.
scite1: "Belarus arrests three after blast at KGB: official," Agence France Presse -- English, November 12, 2012.
scite2: "Belarus arrests three suspects after blast outside KGB building," Xinhua General News Service, November 12, 2012.
scite3: "Belarus arrests three suspects after blast outside KGB building," Xinhua News Agency, November 12, 2012.
